  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Sets global standards for combating money laundering\n- 40 recommendations widely adopted by countries worldwide\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Provides framework for international cooperation\n- Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision guidelines\n- Establishes banking sector standards for detecting and preventing money laundering\n\n4. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Sets regulations for EU member states\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n\n5. Bank Secrecy Act (U.S. law with international implications)\n- Requires financial institutions to assist government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering\n\nThese laws typically require:\n- Customer identification\n- Transaction monitoring\n- Reporting of suspicious activities\n- Cooperation between countries\n- Penalties for non-compliance\n\nMost countries have also developed their own national anti-money laundering laws aligned with these international standards.",
